      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Property with a Body Corporate in Brisbane: What Owners Need to Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Units and townhouses in Brisbane's inner east come with disclosure obligations most sellers have not thought about. Here is what buyers will ask for, what you must provide, and how to get ahead of the process.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling a freestanding house in Brisbane is relatively straightforward from a disclosure standpoint. Selling a unit or townhouse within a community title scheme is more involved. The body corporate adds a layer of information that buyers, their solicitors, and their lenders will all want to see before committing. If you are selling a lot within a body corporate scheme in Brisbane's inner east, understanding what you need to provide and what buyers will discover through their own searches is essential preparation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The body corporate disclosure statement</h2>
      <p>Under Queensland property law, you are required to attach a body corporate disclosure statement to the contract of sale when selling a lot in a community title scheme. This document is prepared by the body corporate manager or the lot owner and must contain specific information prescribed under the <em>Body Corporate and Community Management Act 1997 (Qld)</em>.</p>

      <p>The disclosure statement must include the current administrative and sinking fund levy amounts payable by the lot, any special levies that have been raised or are proposed, the name and contact details of the body corporate manager, and any information about insurance. If the disclosure statement contains a material error or omission, the buyer has the right to terminate the contract within a specified period after becoming aware of the discrepancy. Getting this document right matters.</p>

      <p>Your first step before going to market should be contacting your body corporate manager to request an up-to-date disclosure statement and a summary of the current financial position of the scheme. This puts you ahead of buyer queries rather than scrambling to respond once you are under contract.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers will search for independently</h2>
      <p>Beyond the disclosure statement attached to the contract, buyers and their solicitors routinely commission a body corporate records search. This is a separate document ordered from the body corporate manager that provides a comprehensive picture of the scheme's financial and administrative health. It typically includes meeting minutes from the past year or two (general and committee meetings), the current and historical budgets, the sinking fund balance and any sinking fund forecast, details of any outstanding or recent litigation, current insurance certificates, and records of any known defects in common property.</p>

      <p>This search is not within your control. Buyers purchase it directly from the body corporate manager and receive whatever is on record. That is why the condition of your building's common property matters to your sale. A body corporate with a healthy sinking fund, well-maintained common areas, and well-documented financials will present clearly and cleanly. One with deferred maintenance, inadequate insurance, or a history of unresolved disputes will raise flags that cost you in either price or buyer attrition.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Special levies: the most common source of delay</h2>
      <p>Special levies are raised when the body corporate needs to fund works beyond what the sinking fund can cover. Major roof repairs, lift refurbishments, concrete rectification, and external painting are the most common triggers in Brisbane's older inner-east unit stock. If a special levy has been raised, is in the process of being raised, or is likely to be raised within the near term, this information must be disclosed and will typically reduce the price a buyer is willing to pay, or cause them to factor the levy cost directly into their offer.</p>

      <p>If you know a special levy is coming and you sell before it is formally voted on and issued, you need to be careful about disclosure. Buyers who later discover a special levy was foreseeable at the time of sale and was not mentioned may have grounds for a claim. Your conveyancer or solicitor can advise on your specific obligations. The safe approach is disclosure rather than omission.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How body corporate affects buyer finance</h2>
      <p>When a buyer's lender assesses the purchase of a unit in a body corporate scheme, they look at two things beyond the standard serviceability calculation. First, they assess the levies as an ongoing expense that affects the buyer's capacity to service the loan. High levies reduce borrowing capacity, and buyers in tightly managed budget situations may not qualify for the amount they need if levies are above a lender's threshold. Second, lenders check that the building is adequately insured. Buildings with insurance that does not reflect current replacement cost, or schemes that have allowed insurance to lapse or be reduced, can trigger a lender refusal.</p>

      <p>This is not a hypothetical risk in Brisbane's inner east. Buildings constructed in the 1970s and 1980s, common in Coorparoo, Camp Hill, and Morningside, sometimes have body corporate managers who have not updated insurance coverage to reflect genuine rebuild costs. A buyer who proceeds to finance conditional and then has their lender flag an underinsurance issue faces a genuine problem that can kill a deal or require renegotiation. As a seller, you have limited ability to fix this once a contract is signed. The time to understand your scheme's insurance position is before the marketing campaign begins.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing for the campaign</h2>
      <p>The practical steps that will make your sale smoother are straightforward. Request an up-to-date copy of the body corporate disclosure statement from your manager. Read the most recent AGM minutes to understand what has been discussed and decided. Check whether there are any outstanding defect notices on common property. Confirm the current sinking fund balance relative to the sinking fund plan. If the fund is underfunded against the plan, understand why and be prepared to explain it.</p>

      <p>If you have access to the body corporate's financials and they show a scheme that is well-managed and financially sound, this is worth mentioning in your marketing. Buyers in the inner east who have been through the process before know that body corporate quality varies enormously between buildings in the same street. A building with transparent management, adequate reserves, and a maintenance programme that is actually followed is a genuine point of difference.</p>

      <p>Your conveyancer will handle the formal disclosure requirements. Your role as the seller is to make sure they have accurate and current information to work with, and to avoid the kind of late surprises that cause buyers to renegotiate or walk away during the due diligence period.</p>

